{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472394"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.08,0.71,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92446"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1351"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"715"},{"type":"tags","id":"11442"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31635"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92446"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with acute urinary retention and perineal pain. His family recently migrated from Malaysia. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears distressed with vital signs within normal limits. His lower abdomen is tender with a palpable bladder. A pelvic X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phlebolith","Sacrococcygeal teratoma","Urethral calculus","Faecolith","Fractured pelvis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray demonstrates a radio-opaque density in the region of the urethra, consistent with a urethral calculus. The clinical presentation of acute urinary retention and perineal pain in a child from an endemic stone region strongly supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrethral calculi\u003C/strong\u003E are relatively uncommon in children but are more frequently seen in regions with endemic urinary tract stone disease, such as parts of Southeast Asia. They typically present with acute urinary retention, dysuria, and perineal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ephlebolith\u003C/strong\u003E is a calcified thrombosis within a vein that appears as a small, round radio-opaque density. However, phleboliths are typically multiple and are found incidentally in asymptomatic patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esacrococcygeal teratoma\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a complex mass arising from the sacrococcygeal region, often with both solid and cystic components. It typically presents in infancy and would not cause acute urinary retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecolith\u003C/strong\u003E is a hardened mass of faeces that can become calcified. While it can appear radio-opaque on X-ray, it would be located within the bowel lumen and would present with constipation rather than urinary symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efractured pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E would show disruption of the normal bony architecture. There is no history of trauma, and the pelvic bones appear intact on the X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urethral calculi appear as radio-opaque densities along the course of the urethra on plain radiographs.","Urethral calculi are more common in regions with endemic urinary tract stone disease.","Children with urethral calculi typically present with acute urinary retention and perineal pain."],"references":["Kamal BA, Anikwe RM, Darawani H, Hashish M, Taha SA. Urethral calculi: presentation and management. BJU Int. 2004 Mar;93(4):549-52. doi: 10.1111/j.1464-410x.2003.04660.x. PMID: 15008727."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"324"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/324"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/25141be9-5096-4c16-aa11-7621f66d4178.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/25141be9-5096-4c16-aa11-7621f66d4178.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":320,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T20:07:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T20:07:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1351"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92446"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11